#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn how to use Spack environments to manage reproducible software stacks "
"on a local machine."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:11
msgid "Spack Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:13
msgid ""
"Spack is a powerful package manager designed for the complex software needs "
"of supercomputers. These same robust features for managing versions and "
"dependencies also make it an excellent tool for local development on a "
"laptop or workstation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:16
msgid ""
"If you are used to tools like Conda, Homebrew or pip for managing local "
"command-line tools and development projects, you will find Spack "
"environments to be a powerful and flexible alternative. Spack environments "
"allow you to create self-contained, reproducible software collections, a "
"concept similar to Conda environments and Python's virtual environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:19
msgid ""
"Unlike other package managers, Spack environments do not contain copies of "
"the software themselves. Instead, they reference installations in the Spack "
"store, which is a central location where Spack keeps all installed packages. "
"This means that multiple environments can share the same package "
"installations, saving disk space and reducing duplication."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:23
msgid ""
"In this section, we will walk through creating a simple environment to "
"manage a personal software stack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:26
msgid "Creating and Activating an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:28
msgid ""
"First, let's create and activate a new environment. This places you "
"\"inside\" the environment, so all subsequent Spack commands apply to it by "
"default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:31
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv\n"
"==> Created environment myenv in /path/to/spack/var/spack/environments/"
"myenv\n"
"$ spack env activate myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:37
msgid "Here, *myenv* is the name of our new environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:39
msgid "You can verify you are in the environment using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:41
msgid ""
"$ spack env status\n"
"==> In environment myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:47
msgid "Adding Specs to the Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:49
msgid ""
"Now that our environment is active, we can add the packages we want to "
"install. Let's say we want a newer version of curl and a few Python "
"libraries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:52
msgid "$ spack add curl@8 python py-numpy py-scipy py-matplotlib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:56
msgid ""
"You can add packages one at a time or all at once. Notice that we didn't "
"need to specify the environment name, as Spack knows we are working inside "
"``myenv``. These packages are now added to the environment's manifest file, "
"``spack.yaml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:60
msgid "You can view the manifest at any time by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:62
msgid "$ spack config edit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:66
msgid "This will open your ``spack.yaml``, which should look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:68
msgid "Example ``spack.yaml`` for our environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:68
msgid ""
"# This is a Spack Environment file.\n"
"#\n"
"# It describes a set of packages to be installed, along with\n"
"# configuration settings.\n"
"spack:\n"
"  # add package specs to the `specs` list\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - curl@8\n"
"  - python\n"
"  - py-numpy\n"
"  - py-scipy\n"
"  - py-matplotlib\n"
"  view: true\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:87
msgid ""
"The ``view: true`` setting tells Spack to create a single directory where "
"all executables, libraries, etc., are symlinked together, similar to a "
"traditional Unix prefix. By default, this view is located inside the "
"environment directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:91
msgid "Installing the Software"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:93
msgid ""
"With our specs defined, the next step is to have Spack solve the dependency "
"graph. This is called \"concretization.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:96
msgid ""
"$ spack concretize\n"
"==> Concretized ...\n"
" ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:102
msgid ""
"Spack will find a consistent set of versions and dependencies for the "
"packages you requested. Once this is done, you can install everything with a "
"single command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:105
msgid "$ spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:109
msgid ""
"Spack will now download, build, and install all the necessary packages. "
"After the installation is complete, the environment's view is automatically "
"updated. Because the environment is active, your ``PATH`` and other "
"variables are already configured."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:113
msgid "You can verify the installation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:115
msgid ""
"$ which python3\n"
"/path/to/spack/var/spack/environments/myenv/.spack-env/view/bin/python3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:120
msgid ""
"When you are finished working in the environment, you can deactivate it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:122 ../../../environments_basics.rst:170
msgid "$ spack env deactivate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:127
msgid "Keeping Up With Updates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:129
msgid ""
"Over time, you may want to update the packages in your environment to their "
"latest versions. Spack makes this easy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:132
msgid ""
"First, update Spack's package repository to make the latest package versions "
"available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:134
msgid "$ spack repo update"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:138
msgid "Then, activate the environment, re-concretize and reinstall."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:140
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack concretize --fresh-roots --force\n"
"$ spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:146
msgid ""
"The ``--fresh-roots`` flag tells the concretizer to prefer the latest "
"available package versions you've added explicitly to the environment, while "
"allowing existing dependencies to remain unchanged if possible. "
"Alternatively, you can use the ``--fresh`` flag to prefer the latest "
"versions of all packages including dependencies, but that might lead to "
"longer install times and more changes. The ``--force`` flag allows it to "
"overwrite the previously solved dependencies. The ``install`` command is "
"smart and will only build packages that are not already installed for the "
"new configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:152
msgid "Cleaning Up Old Packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:154
msgid ""
"After an update, you may have old, unused packages taking up space. You can "
"safely remove any package that is no longer part of an environment's "
"dependency tree."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:157 ../../../environments_basics.rst:183
msgid "$ spack gc --except-any-environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:161
msgid ""
"This runs Spack's garbage collector, which will find and uninstall any "
"package versions that are no longer referenced by *any* of your environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:164
msgid "Removing the Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:166
msgid "If you no longer need an environment, you can completely remove it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:168
msgid "First, ensure the environment is not active:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:174
msgid "Then, remove the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:176
msgid "$ spack env rm myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:180
msgid ""
"This removes the environment's directory and its view, but the packages that "
"were installed for it remain in the Spack store. To actually remove the "
"installations from the Spack store and free up disk space, you can run the "
"garbage collector again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:187
msgid ""
"This command will safely uninstall any packages that are no longer "
"referenced by any of your remaining environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:190
msgid "Next steps"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments_basics.rst:192
msgid ""
"Spack has many other features for managing software environments. See :doc:"
"`environments` for more advanced usage."
msgstr ""
